\section{In-Code Commenting Style}

\subsection{Docstrings}
All public functions must have docstrings using Julia's triple-quote syntax:
\begin{lstlisting}
"""
    function_name(arg1, arg2) -> ReturnType

Brief description.

# Arguments
- `arg1::Type`: Description
- `arg2::Type`: Description

# Returns
- `ReturnType`: Description

# Examples
```julia
result = function_name(1.0, 2.0)
```
"""
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{Inline Comments}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Use \texttt{\#} for single-line comments
    \item Use \texttt{\#= ... =\#} for multi-line comments
    \item If a line of code is temporary (e.g., just for testing), use the comment \texttt{\# temp}
    \item Comment \textit{why}, not \textit{what} (code should be self-documenting)
\end{itemize}

